%% вӢ•
%% Design guidelines:
%% 1. All operators can be constructed from atomic primitives
%% 2. Operators can be unary (takes previous operator result) or binary (takes previous operator result and second operand)
%% 3. User enters initial seed value, operators, and binary operands. A combDOM_nation operator and second operand are a "operation slot"
%% 4. Values for seeds and binary operands can be digits 0-9
%% 
%% Theoretical progression path:
%% - Every subgraph defines its own calculator, which starts with its own settings, primitives, and visualizer locked in place (at first).
%% - Every calculator is equipped with the settings required to reason about that family of operators and intuitively understand the results.
%% - The player starts with the increment operator only, and must construct other operators to earn the right to think that way.
%% - All of the main arithmetic functions can be inverted. Sometimes inverses imply the existence of new numbers.
%% - Sometimes, using operators on these new types of numbers can have interesting outcomes
%% - Finding an interesting outcome in a new area unlocks a new calculator with that new outcome as an installed defined operator key
%% - New unlocks from within a family are added to that calculator directly - not yet freely movable
%% - Once all of an operator's child nodes are in play, that operator is free to swap and add to other calculators
%% - Multiple pathways to the same calculator might be possible, not sure yet
%% - Multiple pathways to the same key might be possible, not sure yet

